social_posts.post_text: A protest was called in to the theater we screened at in Atlanta, by the time we got there it was one person with some inaccurate and irresponsible signs I won’t post here and a mic and speaker. I’d hoped to maybe be able to talk to him, but he was yelling at teenage girls to keep their legs closed as they walked in and protecting them was more important than being kind to an angry man in that moment. A majority of Americans want women and all people with a uterus to have access to abortion rights. Bodily autonomy is a basic human right. Don’t let the one loud angry dude scare you off. Thank you so much @renegadefilmfest - this was the most impactful screening we’ve had. (P.S. leave a comment if you want info on getting a hat!)
Tiny little delightful things that bring ✨✨✨ to 30 minutes of the afternoon. 🪩🍄🍄 P.S. love you @thejudgegunn

Hi. It’s me. @tashalitas. Besides driving the camera truck, moving lights, and sweeping sets, I also directed “Abigail” a verbatim reading of letters between Abigail Adams (@milano_alyssa) and John Adams (@thejudgegunn) in 1776 - guess what she wanted? A country formed with equal rights for women! 247 years later, the ERA was never ratified and the Supreme Court can take away bodily autonomy - a basic human right. @milano_alyssa and @thejudgegunn battle it out through colonial text. Come meet us at @overlookfilmfest this Sunday 4/2 at 3:30pm and enjoy a horrifying journey from the past and future of women’s rights and reproductive rights for all genders! Shoutout to @gisellerella who brought up these letters as an idea 4 days before we started filming. 
Staring Alyssa Milano & Sean Gunn

Hello from @musicboxchicago with @givemeanafilm @xyzfilms and @midwest_access_coalition. It’s been almost a year since Roe v. Wade was overturned and it really effed up my life, but not nearly as bad as it’s effed up a whole lot of other peoples’ lives who are deeply affected by this in states where abortions are banned, health is threatened, rights have been taken away. Grateful for the many many many people who made this film and are now bringing this film to an audience so that we can all keep fighting. Bodily autonomy is a human right. Period.

Art has always been political. It’s used to start conversations, discuss difficult topics, ask for change. A year ago women and people with ovaries all lost their right to bodily autonomy (a basic human right) and to reproductive healthcare in the US. Women became second class citizens without say over their own bodies. I’m not here to fight about the nuances of abortion, I’m here to fight for people to have decisions over their own bodies. I’m here to say taking rights from any group of people (uhh… women) is a slippery slope to taking rights from other groups of people. It’s not my business to know if there was rape or incest, or if it’s family planning, or the details of someone’s health that could be in danger or just someone’s decision, it’s my business to use my voice and privilege (y’all it’s a damn privilege to make a film) to stand up for other women and people with ovaries. It is my business to protect women and protect each other. Please support us as we release this film into the world - screenings in select cities this week then to VOD June 29. (Link in bio)

We had a 10 hour layover in Istanbul last week and squeezed in a sunset dinner on the Bosphorus and late night trip to the Hagia Sofia. I’ve always wanted to see the Hagia Sofia and I legit cried - it’s such an incredible confluence of history and everything about it feels like a sacred place. It was built in 537 under Roman rule and was a church (orthodox and then catholic) for almost a thousand years before it became a Mosque in 1453 with the Ottoman conquest. The minaretes were added in the 15th and 16th century. It used to have a marble exterior (marble! It must have been gorgeous!), then brick and was plastered  with stucco in the 19th century. The blue mosque across the way is also gorgeous, but, it’s like a thousand years newer! This building, that was first built as a Christian church, became the prototype for thousands of years of mosques to come - it’s such an important place to take a step back and see how humanity, religion, culture are all so woven together. We’re a really complicated little world, but also not that complicated. I hope I get to go back to Istanbul for more than 10 hours someday and can go to the spice market, eat more food, take a boat out on the Bosporus, listen to music, dance with people, talk to people.

Spent less time in Amsterdam than we wanted to cause canceling flights is super popular with the airlines these days, but had an amazing 20ish hours filled with more than one delicious meal and even snuck in a boat tour. Boat tour told us all about how the Dutch East India Company built up Amsterdam as we know it in the 1600s because the spices they traded were so so so so very expensive. All I gotta say is they weren’t making all that money off the spices. The world is a complicated and very interwoven place. I love it all so but also am always trying to understand it better and learn from history, even when it’s trying to be hidden.

Happy New Year! Instagram got dark for me this past year but I actually really like the medium of sharing my favorite photos so gonna try that again for 2024: This is from a walk after an eff-off-this-is-so-good dinner at @spagomaui Jan 1 and I love that these photos remind me of the entire dinner - the conversations, the food, my friends and family - without being an actual photo of dinner. Even without relating it to all that, there’s some sort of still magic in these photos that really feels like the reset of a new year. I’m here for the joyful photos 2024, please don’t let me down! (If anyone wants to talk politics, climate change, the dangers of AI, the dangers of Kaiju just call me, invite me to coffee, look me in the eye and talk to me - I just can’t do it here.) Love you all. Happy 2024!
